# 🔐 **Option 2: Private S3 (Signed request – FIXED version of your script)**

Your original script tried to do signing but had multiple errors. Here’s the **correct version (AWS Signature V2 style)**:

```bash
#!/bin/bash

bucket="$1"
file="$2"
filename="$3"

endpoint="s3.example.com"
access_key="YOUR_ACCESS_KEY"
secret_key="YOUR_SECRET_KEY"

logdir="/tmp"
contentType="application/octet-stream"

if [ -z "$bucket" ] || [ -z "$file" ] || [ -z "$filename" ]; then
  echo "Usage: $0 <bucket> <file> <output_filename>"
  exit 1
fi

dateValue=$(date -R)
resource="/${bucket}/${file}"

stringToSign="GET\n\n${contentType}\n${dateValue}\n${resource}"

signature=$(echo -en "$stringToSign" | openssl sha1 -hmac "$secret_key" -binary | base64)

authHeader="Authorization: AWS ${access_key}:${signature}"

url="https://${bucket}.${endpoint}/${file}"

echo "Downloading from: $url"

set -x
curl -f -o "${logdir}/${filename}" \
  -H "Date: ${dateValue}" \
  -H "Content-Type: ${contentType}" \
  -H "${authHeader}" \
  "$url"
set +x

echo "Saved to: ${logdir}/${filename}"
```

